                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, June 13: Mediclaim policyholders, who are insured for a sum of Rs 1 lakh and above, will soon be able to switch to another insurer without any change in the premium outgo. It has been decided to widen the cover, according to the recommendations of the General Insurance Council, an association of non-life insurers. Issues have been sorted out and it has been suggested that portability will be allowed for sum insured of Rs 1 lakh and above, S.L. Mohan, secretary-general of the General Insurance Council, said.                            
	 New Delhi, June 13: The government will sell its residual stakes in metal firms Bharat Aluminium Company (Balco) and Hindustan Zinc (HZL) at a much higher price as the strategic sale of equity in these firms was done in haste, mines minister B.K. Handique said. Divestment in Balco and HZL was done in haste. I feel it needs to be more priced, he said.                             
	 New Delhi, June 13: Exporters, especially from labour-intensive sectors, can expect some additional sops as the commerce ministry has completed its second sectoral review. The ministry had started its review on April 1 to finalise incentives to encourage shipments to help achieve the $200-billion target this fiscal.                             
	 New Delhi, June 13: Fifteen companies, including British Telecom, have been shortlisted by the government to select a telecom vendor, which will certify equipment imported by various mobile firms, especially from China.                             
	 Mumbai, June 13: Reflecting buoyant economic activities, payments made through debit cards zoomed over 40 per cent to Rs 2,508 crore in April compared with the same month last year, according to the RBI.                            
	 Mumbai, June 13: Private sector lender Dhanalaxmi Bank plans to raise Rs 350 crore through a qualified institutional placement by the third week of July, a top bank official said today.                            
	 Calcutta, June 13: Bengal environment secretary M.L. Meena is set to become the new chairman of the Calcutta Port Trust. He will assume charge this week.                                                                                                                           
